<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[150,1436,1130,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
The identity of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[345,575,1131,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[345,575,1131,1156]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Ommatius flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[637,832,1131,1156]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[637,832,1131,1156]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been uncertain for many years. The original descriptions of the 2 species are very similar, and are without comparable diagnostic characters. Hence museum specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[430,562,1205,1230]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[430,562,1205,1230]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may have labels with either name. Unfortunately, the description of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, including the male terminalia, could be confused with that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[972,1155,1243,1268]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[972,1155,1243,1268]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Loew, H." box="[1170,1321,1242,1268]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="73 - 402" refId="ref23648" refString="Loew, H. (1860) Die Dipteren fauna Sudafrika. Abhandlungen des Naturweissenshafttlichen, 2, 73 - 402. (Asilidae pp. 128 - 224). Halle." type="journal article" year="1860">Loew (1860)</bibRefCitation>
noted the deeply notched epandrium with small denticles and 
<bibRefCitation author="Ricardo, G." box="[768,947,1280,1306]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="161 - 178" refId="ref24375" refString="Ricardo, G. (1900) Notes on Diptera from South Africa. Tabanidae and Asilidae. Annals and Magazine of Natural History (7) 6, 161 - 178. London." type="journal article" year="1900">Ricardo (1900)</bibRefCitation>
reported the color of the male terminalia but neither provided an illustration of it. The epandria of both species have a deep apical notch (
<figureCitation box="[1272,1369,1317,1343]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[151,1436,269,1897]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew), male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, A. flavipes; 18. Type labels, A. flavipes. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1382,1414,1317,1343]" captionStart="FIGURES 30–36" captionStartId="12.[150,271,1898,1922]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,203,1857]" captionTargetId="figure-61@12.[150,1436,194,1877]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 30–36. Longibeccus fuscovittatus (Ricardo), male wing and terminalia. 30. Right wing; 31–33. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 34. Gonostylus; 35–36. Aedeagus, dorsal and lateral views. Abbr.: r4, m3=cells; cerc=cercus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">31</figureCitation>
). The confused taxonomy originated with 
<bibRefCitation author="Bromley, S. W." box="[667,890,1354,1380]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" refId="ref23071" refString="Bromley, S. W. (1936) Studies in South African Asilidae (Diptera). Annals of the Transvaal Museum, 18,125 - 146. Pertoria." type="book" year="1936">Bromley’s (1936)</bibRefCitation>
study of 
<collectingCountry box="[1013,1174,1354,1380]" name="South Africa" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">South Africa</collectingCountry>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[1185,1312,1355,1380]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1185,1312,1355,1380]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Ommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
where he misidentified 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[318,507,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[318,507,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[549,680,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[549,680,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[820,951,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[820,951,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a new species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bromley" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[1176,1308,1392,1417]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[1176,1308,1392,1417]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and the 2 names in a key while excluding 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2010" box="[530,714,1429,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Longibeccus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[530,714,1429,1454]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. fuscovittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Subsequently, others perpetuated the error by using this key. Initially 
<bibRefCitation author="Oldroyd, H." box="[254,442,1466,1492]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="1 - 171" refId="ref24231" refString="Oldroyd, H. (1974) An introduction of the robber flies (Diptera: Asilidae) of Southern Africa. Annals of the Natal Museum, 22, 1 - 171. Pietermaritzburg." type="journal article" year="1974">Oldroyd (1974)</bibRefCitation>
questioned Bromley’s identification of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[922,1052,1467,1492]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[922,1052,1467,1492]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, commented on the species and included an illustration of the male terminalia. Unfortunately his illustration does not correspond well with specimens carrying his labels. For example, the diagnostic apical notch of the epandrium is not included in the illustration even though it is clearly visible in his dissections / slides (see Natal / Weenen / 
<date box="[1321,1417,1578,1604]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1924-03">iii.1924</date>
/ [terminalia slide 53] / H.P. Thomasset ~ 
<taxonomicName authority="Ric." authorityName="Ricardo" authorityYear="1900" box="[634,970,1616,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fuscovittatus">
<emphasis box="[634,912,1616,1641]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Ommatius fuscovittatus</emphasis>
Ric.
</taxonomicName>
/ Det. H. Oldroyd 1973 (
<specimenCount box="[1274,1316,1615,1642]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="male">1 ♂</specimenCount>
, BMNH). Further, he failed to associate specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Bromley" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[685,818,1653,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[685,818,1653,1678]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the BMNH with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[1063,1195,1653,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[1063,1195,1653,1678]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="Oldroyd, H." pageId="6" pageNumber="7" pagination="334 - 373" refId="ref24330" refString="Oldroyd, H. (1980) Family Asilidae. In: Crosskey, R. W. (ed.), Catalogue of Diptera of the Afrotropical Region. British Museum (NH), pp. 334 - 373. London." type="book chapter" year="1980">Oldroyd (1980)</bibRefCitation>
included both species in the Afrotropical catalogue.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="6.[150,1436,1130,2015]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,1727,1753]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Distribution</emphasis>
. Subsaharan Africa (
<collectingCountry box="[605,725,1728,1754]" name="Botswana" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Botswana</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[739,831,1728,1754]" name="Malawi" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Malawi</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[846,904,1728,1754]" name="Serbia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Mali</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[918,1022,1728,1754]" name="Namibia" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Namibia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1036,1191,1728,1754]" name="South Africa" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">South Africa</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1205,1336,1728,1754]" name="Zimbabwe" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Zimbabwe</collectingCountry>
). Adults collected between November and June in grassveld and bushveld communities and tree lined waterways. Perch sites includes tree trunks, grass, bare soil, and mud shores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[150,1436,1130,2015]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1435,152,215]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,315,1839,1865]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Loew" box="[332,588,1840,1865]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[332,588,1840,1865]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Afroestricus flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from congeners by its small size (
<quantity box="[1222,1375,1840,1866]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="7.7" metricValueMin="6.3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="7.0" valueMax="7.7" valueMin="6.3">6.3–7.7 mm</quantity>
) and distinctive terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[417,562,1877,1903]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[151,1436,269,1897]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew), male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, A. flavipes; 18. Type labels, A. flavipes. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Figs. 13–17</figureCitation>
). It is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Scarbrough, 2005" authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2005" box="[758,1112,1877,1903]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sadaukii">
<emphasis box="[758,890,1877,1902]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. sadaukii</emphasis>
Scarbrough, 2005
</taxonomicName>
, but is distinguished by the long, stout, ventral lobe of the epandrium whereas the dorsal corner is much shorter and thin, and the epiphallus is uniformly wide in dorsal view. Additionally, the short carrot-shaped spermathecae distinguish the female. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2005" box="[321,453,1989,2014]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sadaukii">
<emphasis box="[321,453,1989,2014]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">A. sadaukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the ventral corner of the lobed epandrium is contrastingly shorter and weaker than the dorsal corner, and the epiphallus is strongly constricted medially in dorsal view. The somewhat deflated tubelike spermatheca is reflected and the rounded apices further distinguish the female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2005" box="[1204,1336,189,214]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sadaukii">
<emphasis box="[1204,1336,189,214]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. sadaukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<caption pageId="7" pageNumber="8" startId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" targetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1918,2037]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,352,1918,1942]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">FIGURES 13–18.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Loew)" authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Loew" box="[359,672,1918,1942]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[359,582,1919,1942]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Afroestricus flavipes</emphasis>
(Loew)
</taxonomicName>
, male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Loew" box="[998,1115,1951,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[998,1115,1951,1974]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; 18. Type labels, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Loew" box="[1313,1429,1951,1974]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[1313,1429,1951,1974]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">A. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,152,402]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
The male 
<typeStatus box="[316,367,152,178]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[407,628,152,177]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[407,628,152,177]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Ommatius flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in good condition, and has a small squared purple label [Walberg used this color code label for 
<collectingCountry box="[498,649,189,215]" name="South Africa" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">South Africa</collectingCountry>
specimens, but it does not carry a 
<typeStatus box="[1056,1106,189,215]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">type</typeStatus>
label. Labels the pin are: 1) purple square; 2) [rectangle with handwritten] 103; 3) [rectangle with handwritten] 310; 4) [rectangle typeset] 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Scarbrough" baseAuthorityYear="2005" box="[151,273,264,289]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,273,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Ommatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[297,389,264,289]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[297,389,264,289]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; [rectangle with typeset] NHRS-DIPT / 000000007 (
<figureCitation box="[1026,1115,264,290]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–18" captionStartId="7.[151,270,1918,1942]" captionTargetBox="[163,1423,297,1889]" captionTargetId="figure-89@7.[151,1436,269,1897]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 13–18. Afroestricus flavipes (Loew), male terminalia (reillustrated after Scarbrough 2005). 13–15. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 16. Aedeagus, lateral view; 17a–c. Spermathecae, A. flavipes; 18. Type labels, A. flavipes. Abbr.: cerc=cercus; distph=distiphallus; epand=epandrium; epiph= epiphallus; goncx=gonocoxite; hypd=hypandrium; pvapod=posteroventral aedeagal apodeme." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
). The species is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bromley" authorityYear="1936" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Ommatius minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and thus is a junior 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[505,621,301,327]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">synonym</emphasis>
of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1860" box="[666,800,301,326]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavipes">
<emphasis box="[666,800,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">O. flavipes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Recently, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bromley" authorityYear="1936" box="[942,1174,301,326]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="minutus">
<emphasis box="[942,1174,301,326]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Ommatius minutus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was redescribed, the terminalia of both sexes were illustrated, and transferred to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scarbrough" authorityYear="2005" box="[867,1011,338,363]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Afroestricus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[867,1011,338,363]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Afroestricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Scarbrough 2005; see pgs. 35–39, 
<figureCitation box="[151,293,376,402]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 79–82" captionStart-1="FIGURES 83–88" captionStart-2="FIGURES 89–94" captionStartId-0="31.[151,277,1974,1998]" captionStartId-1="33.[151,271,1971,1995]" captionStartId-2="35.[151,272,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox-0="[204,1392,446,1943]" captionTargetBox-1="[233,1373,489,1938]" captionTargetBox-2="[159,1427,211,1829]" captionTargetId-0="figure-132@31.[191,1402,433,1972]" captionTargetId-1="figure-152@33.[215,1380,451,1964]" captionTargetId-2="figure-70@35.[151,1436,194,1851]" captionTargetPageId-0="31" captionTargetPageId-1="33" captionTargetPageId-2="35" captionText-0="FIGURES 79–82. Ommatius neotenellus Bromley, female terminalia. 79–80. Dorsal and ventral views; 81. Spermathecae; 82. Genital fork." captionText-1="FIGURES 83–88. Ommatius prolixus n. sp., male, wing and terminalia. 83. Right wing. 84–86. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 87. Aedeagus, lateral view; 88. Gonostylus." captionText-2="FIGURES 89–94. Ommatius ultimus n. sp., male, wing and terminalia. 89. Right wing. 90–92. Lateral, dorsal, and ventral views; 93. Gonostylus; 94. Aedeagus, lateral view." pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Figs. 81–90</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
